# 
# https://dataout.org/ontology#Defendant
<https://dataout.org/ontology#Defendant> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#Defendant> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A legal or natural person with a role of a defendant in a legal process."@en .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#Defendant> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Defendant"@en .
# 
# https://dataout.org/ontology#MonitoringActivity
<https://dataout.org/ontology#MonitoringActivity> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#MonitoringActivity> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#Activity> .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#MonitoringActivity> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Class representing a single monitoring activity. Dataout conducts monitorings of different categories, such as hate crimes, discrimination, administrative and criminal persecution. The categories of monitoring are defined by the MonitoringCategoryScheme."@en .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#MonitoringActivity> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Monitoring Activity"@en .
# 
# https://dataout.org/ontology#MonitoringRecord
<https://dataout.org/ontology#MonitoringRecord> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#MonitoringRecord> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#Entity> .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#MonitoringRecord> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A single record resulting from a monitoring activity. For example, if a monitoring activity documents hate crime incidents, an entity representing a hate crime would be a monitoring record."@en .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#MonitoringRecord> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Monitoring Record"@en .
# 
# https://dataout.org/ontology#Penalty
<https://dataout.org/ontology#Penalty> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#Penalty> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Penalty imposed by an official body, such as a court."@en .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#Penalty> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Penalty"@en .
# 
# https://dataout.org/ontology#Source
<https://dataout.org/ontology#Source> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#Source> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#Entity> .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#Source> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A source of a monitoring record indicating provenance information."@en .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#Source> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Source"@en .
# 
# https://dataout.org/ontology#TriggerObject
<https://dataout.org/ontology#TriggerObject> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#TriggerObject> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A trigger object is an information object or public action that was used by the authorities as a reason to initiate an administrative or criminal proceeding. For example, in our monitoring of administrative persecution targeting LGBTQIA+ expression in Russia, a trigger object could be a mass media publication, which the Russian mass media regulator (Roskomnadzor) found to be violating, which resulted in a court case against a media company dissimianting such publication."@en .
<https://dataout.org/ontology#TriggerObject> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Trigger Object"@en .
